	 JavaScript AJAX techiniques:
	 
	1. XMLHttpsRequest
			-it is browser object used to make AJAX calls in browser
			-it is native object of borwser
			
	 
	a) Configure a reference for XMLHttpsRequest
	
		let http = new XMLHttpsRequest();
		
	b) Configure the request by using "open()" method
	http.open("method","url", async:boolean);
	
	method 		:GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, PURGE, DELETE
	url 		: refers to request path
	async 		:true will use unblocking technique false with use bloking technique.
	c) Send the request by using "send()" method
			http.send();
	d) Execute request by using "onreadystatechange" event
	
	http.onreadystatechange = function() {
	
	}
	
	-Request is processed in 4 states
		1  	initial
		2  	Success
		3  	Complete State
		4	Ready State
	
	classless inter domine routing
	
	e) Fetch data on ready state
	
		if(http.readyState === 4)
	{
		// you can acess the response
		// response can be in various format
		
		http.responseText 	[string format]
		http.respnseXML		[xml format]
	}
		
		The default respnse format is"text".
		if your data is not text or xml then itrequires explicit parsing.
	
	
1. XMLHttpsRequest in React
	
	-React can use XMLHttpsRequest object
	-it can handle AJAXrequestusing XMLHttpRequest

Issues	
	 -it is browser object
	 -React uses Virtual DOM,hencebrowser object are not recommended.
	 -it is not async by default it requires explicit async configuration.
	 -it return response in Text OR XML only. it requires explicit conversions for other data types.
	 -Converting datamy lead to CORS issues.
	 -Secuirity issues
	 -It is not good in error handling.
	 
2. Javascript "fetch()" promise

 - Promise is async by default
 - It returns data in binary format.
 - It requires explicit conversions.
 - It is simplified when compared to XMLHttpRequest.
 - It is better in error handling.
 
Syntax:
		fetch("url")
		.then(function(response){return response.json()})
		.then(function(data){})
		.catch(function(error) {})
		.finally(function() {'excecute always'})
	 
	 
issues  with fetch() in react

	-it returns data in binary.
	-Explicit conversions are required.[COM to Marshal]
	-CORS issues.
	- XSRF issues [Cross Site Request Forgery]
	-XSS issues [Cross site SCripting attacks]
	-You can't cancel the request.
	
